# Experiment Protocol Standards

This document defines standards for designing and executing experiments: pre-registration, blinding, randomization, outcome measures, and reporting.

---

## Core Principle: Design Before You Measure

Every experiment must have a written protocol before data collection begins. Post-hoc analysis is permitted only when clearly labeled as exploratory.

---

## Pre-Registration

### What to Pre-Register

| Element | Required? | Example |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Primary hypothesis | Yes | "Method A outperforms baseline on metric X" |
| Primary outcome metric | Yes | "F1 score on held-out test set" |
| Sample size / number of runs | Yes | "30 runs with different random seeds" |
| Statistical test | Yes | "Paired t-test, alpha = 0.05" |
| Exclusion criteria | Yes | "Runs that fail to converge within 100 epochs" |
| Secondary hypotheses | Recommended | "Method A also improves metric Y" |
| Analysis pipeline | Recommended | "Link to analysis script in repo" |

### Pre-Registration Process

1. Write the protocol document before running experiments
2. Commit the protocol to version control with a dated tag
3. Do not modify the protocol after data collection begins
4. If protocol changes are necessary: document amendments with dates and rationale
5. Analysis that deviates from protocol is labeled "exploratory" in results

---

## Experimental Design

### Randomization

| Design | When to Use | Implementation |
|--------|-------------|---------------|
| Simple random | Independent observations | `random.shuffle` with fixed seed |
| Stratified random | Ensure balance across groups | Group by stratum, then randomize within |
| Block random | Small sample sizes | Assign in blocks of size 2k |
| Cross-validation | Limited data | k-fold with fixed seed |
| Time-series split | Temporal data | Walk-forward, no future leakage |

### Randomization Checklist

- [ ] Randomization method is documented
- [ ] Random seed is recorded
- [ ] Balance across groups is verified post-randomization
- [ ] No peeking at results before randomization is complete

### Control Conditions

Every experiment must include at least one control:

| Control Type | Purpose | Example |
|-------------|---------|---------|
| Baseline (no treatment) | Establish expected performance | Random predictor, majority class |
| Ablation (remove component) | Isolate contribution of each part | Model without feature X |
| Oracle (upper bound) | Understand ceiling performance | Human performance, perfect information |
| Prior work (reproduction) | Validate experimental setup | Re-implement published result |

---

## Blinding

### Blinding Levels

| Level | Description | When Required |
|-------|-------------|---------------|
| No blinding | Analyst knows conditions | Exploratory analysis |
| Single blind | Analyst does not know which condition is "new" | Confirmatory results |
| Double blind | Neither analyst nor data collector knows | Clinical / high-stakes |

### Blinding in Computational Experiments

- [ ] Analysis scripts process all conditions identically (no condition-specific code paths)
- [ ] Results are reported for all conditions, not just favorable ones
- [ ] Condition labels can be shuffled without changing the analysis pipeline
- [ ] Hyperparameter tuning is applied equally to all conditions

---

## Outcome Measures

### Primary vs. Secondary

| Type | Definition | Handling |
|------|-----------|----------|
| Primary | The one metric that answers the hypothesis | Powers the study, corrected for multiplicity |
| Secondary | Supporting metrics | Reported but not used for primary claim |
| Exploratory | Interesting observations | Clearly labeled, no p-value claims |

### Metric Selection Criteria

- [ ] Metric is well-defined (unambiguous computation from data)
- [ ] Metric is relevant to the real-world objective
- [ ] Metric is sensitive to the expected effect (can detect the difference)
- [ ] Metric is robust to outliers (or outlier handling is defined)
- [ ] Metric has known behavior under the null hypothesis

### Metric Reporting

| Metric | Mean | Std Dev | Median | IQR | Min | Max | N |
|--------|------|---------|--------|-----|-----|-----|---|
| | | | | | | | |

Always report: central tendency, dispersion, and sample size.

---

## Experiment Execution

### Run Management

| Requirement | Implementation |
|-------------|---------------|
| Each run has a unique ID | UUID or sequential with timestamp |
| Run configuration is logged | Config file hash + seed |
| Run environment is captured | `pip freeze`, hostname, GPU model |
| Run is recoverable from logs | Can reconstruct exact execution |
| Failed runs are documented | Reason for failure, not silently dropped |

### Execution Checklist

- [ ] Protocol document is committed and tagged before first run
- [ ] All runs use the same code version (git SHA recorded)
- [ ] Runs are independent (no shared state between runs)
- [ ] Failed runs are counted and reported (not silently excluded)
- [ ] Wall-clock time is recorded for each run (for cost estimation)

---

## Reporting Standards

### Minimum Reporting Requirements

For every claimed result:

1. **What**: Exact metric value with uncertainty (mean +/- std, or CI)
2. **How**: Statistical test used, test statistic, p-value, effect size
3. **Why**: Interpretation in context of the hypothesis
4. **With what**: Exact code version, data version, environment
5. **How many**: Sample size, number of runs, exclusions

### Negative Results

- [ ] Negative results (hypothesis not supported) are reported
- [ ] Non-significant differences are reported with effect size and CI
- [ ] Power analysis for non-significant results (was the study powered to detect the expected effect?)

### Figures and Tables

- [ ] Every figure is generated from a script (not manually created)
- [ ] Error bars or shaded regions show uncertainty (not just mean)
- [ ] Axes are labeled with units
- [ ] Legends are clear and complete
- [ ] Significance annotations use exact p-values (not just asterisks)

---

## Verification Checklist

- [ ] Protocol was written before data collection
- [ ] All pre-registered analyses were performed
- [ ] Exploratory analyses are clearly labeled
- [ ] All runs (including failures) are accounted for
- [ ] Results include effect size and confidence intervals
- [ ] Code and data are available for independent reproduction
